                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.111/126.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-07-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 25, 1913</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The President of Haiti says that, in accord with the Act of 1903, no persons of
                    Syrian origin can come to Haiti and remain permanently. The President has,
                    however, agreed to permit naturalized American citizens of Syrian origin who
                    represent American commercial interests to enter Haiti on the business of their
                    firms if they remain only a few months and if their citizenship and their
                    connection with American commercial concerns are certified by the Department of
                    State or the American Legation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Furniss</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
